WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:16.920
Good afternoon everyone. I'm very excited to announce our last and final keynote, Jeff

00:00:16.920 --> 00:00:23.080
Leek. We are particularly lucky to get Jeff Leek as a keynote speaker right now because

00:00:23.080 --> 00:00:28.040
he's in the middle of a cross-country move to start a new position as VP and Chief Data

00:00:28.040 --> 00:00:41.639
Officer at the Fred Hutchinson Institute for Cancer Research. So Jeff is famous for

00:00:41.639 --> 00:00:46.919
very many things, but two in particular that I wanted to talk about. The first is, along

00:00:46.919 --> 00:00:52.619
with Roger Peng and Brian Caffo, Jeff taught really like the first data science MOOC, which

00:00:52.619 --> 00:01:04.139
introduced R to literally millions of people, which is pretty amazing. The other thing I

00:01:04.139 --> 00:01:10.820
love about Jeff is that him and I disagree on a few things, and one of the things in

00:01:10.820 --> 00:01:17.739
particular, several years ago he wrote a blog post, Why I Don't Use ggplot2. But what I

00:01:17.739 --> 00:01:23.220
love about Jeff's writing is he articulates his position so clearly, like even as I was

00:01:23.220 --> 00:01:29.260
reading that article, I was like nodding along, yeah, yeah, that makes sense. So please join

00:01:29.260 --> 00:01:39.019
me in welcoming Jeff Leek. Thanks very much, and thanks Hadley, I know

00:01:39.019 --> 00:01:43.900
you've been saving that up for a minute. I will say that I have become a ggplot2 convert

00:01:43.900 --> 00:01:52.220
since then, so yes, yes. I'm not even playing to the audience there. Yeah, so I'm very excited

00:01:52.220 --> 00:01:55.940
to be here today to talk to you about Datatrail, which is an effort that we've been running

00:01:55.940 --> 00:02:00.500
in Baltimore for the last four or five years to build inclusive community-based data science

00:02:00.500 --> 00:02:06.940
education, and I hope that you'll be excited to go back into your communities and also

00:02:06.940 --> 00:02:12.220
build programs and connect to your communities. One thing I wanted to start off with, though,

00:02:12.619 --> 00:02:17.419
is I wanted to just say I'm so excited to be in a room with all of you. I've seen tons

00:02:17.419 --> 00:02:22.100
of people that I haven't seen for two and a half years. The very last conference I went

00:02:22.100 --> 00:02:28.419
to in January 2020, before this one, was our studio conference in San Francisco. I then

00:02:28.419 --> 00:02:35.500
got on an airplane, flew back to Baltimore, and the world ended. I know that all of us

00:02:35.500 --> 00:02:40.259
over the last two and a half years have gone through many, many things. They're both individual

00:02:40.259 --> 00:02:44.699
and collective, and I just want to express the joy that I feel to be back together with

00:02:44.699 --> 00:02:48.740
people and back with the R community, and especially this amazing community that the

00:02:48.740 --> 00:02:55.259
band formerly called RStudio has put together. And so I'm really excited about that, and

00:02:55.259 --> 00:02:59.779
I just wanted to express my gratitude both for the invitation to speak here today and

00:02:59.779 --> 00:03:03.179
to the community that's been built, all of you, to coming out and sticking around for

00:03:03.179 --> 00:03:08.220
the last talk. Before I go any further, I also wanted to make sure I thanked the people

00:03:08.220 --> 00:03:15.619
that did all the real important work. This is the Datatrail core team. Ashley Johnson,

00:03:15.619 --> 00:03:21.539
Simone Sawyer, Ed Sabatino, Devon Person, and Ashley and Devon are actually here today,

00:03:21.539 --> 00:03:25.020
and if they could stand up and wave, they're somewhere in the audience. There they are

00:03:25.020 --> 00:03:34.860
right there. Anything good you hear is definitely because of them. Anything silly or misguided

00:03:34.860 --> 00:03:40.339
is due to me. This is a kind of project that can't be done by just a couple of people.

00:03:40.339 --> 00:03:43.660
There's been a huge community of people that have helped us over the years develop the

00:03:43.660 --> 00:03:48.220
Datatrail program, and I just wanted to say that we're so grateful to all the people that

00:03:48.220 --> 00:03:53.100
helped out. One of the things I wanted to talk a little bit about is my own journey

00:03:53.100 --> 00:03:57.220
to where I am here today. As Hadley mentioned, I'm in the middle of a move to take a big,

00:03:57.220 --> 00:04:01.339
exciting new job right near my family, which I'm really excited about, but I didn't start

00:04:01.339 --> 00:04:06.220
there as none of us did. I started off as just a nerdy kid from a very small town in

00:04:06.220 --> 00:04:12.500
Idaho. This is an embarrassing picture that usually other people show in a presentation,

00:04:12.500 --> 00:04:17.459
but how did that happen? How did I go from nerdy kid in Idaho to where I am today? And

00:04:17.459 --> 00:04:22.179
I imagine we all had a similar kind of journey, right? We had to know that this was a field

00:04:22.179 --> 00:04:25.820
which some are just discovering now, some discovered a long time ago. We had to have

00:04:25.820 --> 00:04:29.940
access to the equipment and the training and the connections to be able to be in a room

00:04:29.940 --> 00:04:35.739
here today. But more importantly than that, I had to have help. This is not something

00:04:35.739 --> 00:04:40.299
that I did on my own. I had to be lifted up at various points in my career, from my undergrad

00:04:40.299 --> 00:04:44.739
advisor, Jim Powell, to my grad advisor, John Story, to Giovanni Parmigiani, who recruited

00:04:44.739 --> 00:04:49.820
me to Baltimore by saying, do you want to live near your wife, to Rafa Irizarry, who

00:04:49.820 --> 00:04:54.140
was my main faculty mentor in my early years, and many, many other people who have worked

00:04:54.140 --> 00:04:59.299
with me. Just like me, I'm sure you feel the same way, that there are people that have

00:04:59.299 --> 00:05:03.420
helped you out in your life. And so I wanted to just take a minute, because we're all here

00:05:03.420 --> 00:05:07.859
together, to turn to your neighbor and maybe tell them about somebody that helped you along

00:05:07.859 --> 00:05:10.980
your way. We're going to just take a minute here, and I'd like you to tell somebody about

00:05:10.980 --> 00:05:14.779
one of your mentors, somebody who helped you out when you had a moment of need. So I'm

00:05:14.779 --> 00:05:17.779
just going to give a brief pause and make it a little interactive. Please talk to your

00:05:17.779 --> 00:05:24.779
neighbor. If you're online, on Discord, you can talk the same way. This is awesome.

00:06:18.779 --> 00:06:25.779
All right. I know that this conversation could last a long time, and I hope you'll

00:06:26.500 --> 00:06:31.500
continue that conversation later. And I hope it reminded you of somebody that helped you

00:06:31.500 --> 00:06:36.940
along the way, because the Datatrail program we're building is about helping other people.

00:06:36.940 --> 00:06:41.579
And so one of the key things that we realize, that I think everybody recognizes, is that

00:06:41.579 --> 00:06:45.980
talent is equally distributed. So these are some young people from our second cohort of

00:06:45.980 --> 00:06:52.660
Datatrail scholars in East Baltimore. These are folks that grew up around there and are

00:06:52.660 --> 00:06:59.540
incredibly talented young people. And there's an important thing that even though the talent

00:06:59.540 --> 00:07:04.100
is equally distributed, opportunity isn't always. So this is data from the Economic

00:07:04.100 --> 00:07:08.739
Opportunity Atlas, and it says that if you were born and grew up in this neighborhood,

00:07:08.739 --> 00:07:15.739
the median family income when you get to age 34 is $18,000 a year. So that whole neighborhood,

00:07:16.019 --> 00:07:20.059
even though it's right next to a multi-billion dollar medical institution, doesn't have access

00:07:20.059 --> 00:07:25.100
to the same career opportunities that, say, I did when I grew up out in Idaho. And it's

00:07:25.100 --> 00:07:28.899
not just Baltimore where this is true. If you look at the Economic Opportunity Atlas,

00:07:28.899 --> 00:07:35.899
where I'm going in Seattle, Pittsburgh, Chicago, Tampa Bay, New York City, no matter where

00:07:35.899 --> 00:07:40.579
you look, there are these opportunity deserts. And so how do we create opportunity in these

00:07:40.579 --> 00:07:45.019
opportunity deserts? How do we actively go out and promote opportunities for folks that

00:07:45.019 --> 00:07:50.019
grew up there? And it's not just economic. It's not just an economic calculation. It's

00:07:50.019 --> 00:07:54.260
also a health calculation. I was in a school of public health. I'm moving to a cancer center.

00:07:54.260 --> 00:07:58.899
I care a lot about health. This is a plot. It doesn't look like real data, but it is

00:07:58.899 --> 00:08:04.980
real data. This is a plot of income percentile on the X axis, and on the Y axis is life expectancy.

00:08:04.980 --> 00:08:09.619
You've got one line for female, one line for male. And you can see that there's like near-perfect

00:08:09.619 --> 00:08:14.420
correlation between how much money your parents made and your life expectancy on average in

00:08:14.420 --> 00:08:19.660
the population, which is kind of incredible. Education is still the best treatment we have

00:08:19.660 --> 00:08:25.700
to cure the problem of lack of opportunity. This is a plot that shows how much your parents made

00:08:25.700 --> 00:08:31.420
on the X axis, and on the Y axis is how much you make after going to different types of schools.

00:08:31.420 --> 00:08:35.659
Each color represents a different type of school. And the lines are relatively flat,

00:08:35.659 --> 00:08:41.059
which means if you get into one of those schools, you have a very good chance of moving up

00:08:41.179 --> 00:08:47.820
economically. But the challenge is you can't always get in. So this is a similar plot. This

00:08:47.820 --> 00:08:53.340
is colleges. Each dot is a college. On the X axis is how likely you are to get into that college

00:08:53.340 --> 00:09:00.260
on a scale from 0 to 100 based on your parents' income. And on the Y axis is how likely you are

00:09:00.260 --> 00:09:06.940
to be in the top quartile of income after completing college there. So places like Johns

00:09:06.940 --> 00:09:10.419
Hopkins, where I used to be at, have very low access. If your parents didn't have a lot of

00:09:10.419 --> 00:09:14.739
money, it's unlikely you're going to get into that college. But if you go there, you're going

00:09:14.739 --> 00:09:19.179
to have a very good chance of having a high economic return. And so you can actually calculate

00:09:19.179 --> 00:09:23.659
this for every college. You can say multiply the probability you get in if you're from the

00:09:23.659 --> 00:09:28.179
lowest quintile of income times the probability you'll be in the highest income once you get out.

00:09:28.179 --> 00:09:32.739
And that can be what we call a mobility rate. This is a calculation developed by some economists.

00:09:32.739 --> 00:09:39.219
And so the best generators of mobility in the United States are typically large public

00:09:39.219 --> 00:09:45.460
institutions, community colleges, technical colleges, that produce the highest level of

00:09:45.460 --> 00:09:51.619
economic mobility in our country. And they're driven by access. So you can see that the success

00:09:51.619 --> 00:09:55.020
rates don't have to be in the high 90s to be. These are the very top colleges in the U.S.

00:09:55.020 --> 00:10:01.099
And it's driven by how accessible that education is. And so we're all here because we love data

00:10:01.099 --> 00:10:07.419
science. We love R. We love Python. We love all the other languages. And it's a high growth and

00:10:07.580 --> 00:10:13.940
wage job category. And so how do we get more people to have access to this? As Hadley mentioned,

00:10:13.940 --> 00:10:18.179
we've been teaching massive online open courses about data science for a long time. And they've

00:10:18.179 --> 00:10:24.419
now enrolled more than 10 million people across the world. And these programs can lead to big

00:10:24.419 --> 00:10:30.179
income gains. So here I'm showing a plot. On the X axis is the cost of the program. And I've got

00:10:30.179 --> 00:10:35.780
graduate school, undergraduate, associate's degree. And on the Y axis is the increase in income post

00:10:36.700 --> 00:10:41.179
program. And for one of our data science sequences, you get nearly the same amount of

00:10:41.179 --> 00:10:46.299
income boost as you would for a college or advanced degree, even for a much lower cost.

00:10:46.299 --> 00:10:50.059
So that seems pretty exciting. And originally we were thinking, okay, this is how we generate

00:10:50.059 --> 00:10:57.820
this mobility at scale. But as not just us, but many, many people have noted, Coursera classes,

00:10:57.820 --> 00:11:02.859
boot camps, those sorts of things, they tend to benefit the already well educated. Most of the

00:11:02.859 --> 00:11:07.419
people taking these programs are actually already have bachelor's degrees, master's degrees,

00:11:07.419 --> 00:11:12.940
professional degrees, and are career transitioning. So we're not really generating access for the

00:11:12.940 --> 00:11:19.739
people that the mobility rate applies to. And so what we try to do is, can we create opportunities

00:11:19.739 --> 00:11:23.659
for the folks that aren't taking the massive online open courses, who haven't been introduced

00:11:23.659 --> 00:11:29.659
to R via these scalable programs? And lest I say that we're the only people thinking about this,

00:11:29.739 --> 00:11:34.059
there are a ton of amazing, I've been to talks today from open scapes to, you know, met amazing

00:11:34.059 --> 00:11:38.380
people from various parts of the world. We got R ladies, we got data carpentry, the bioconductor

00:11:38.380 --> 00:11:43.020
team, so many people that are also trying to do this, to try to lift people up through the power

00:11:43.020 --> 00:11:47.979
of data science education and data science opportunities. But the reality is there are

00:11:47.979 --> 00:11:54.059
significant barriers to entry. I showed this graph a minute ago for myself, but it applies to anyone

00:11:54.059 --> 00:11:57.739
who wants to get into data science. You have to know about data science, you have to have the

00:11:57.739 --> 00:12:03.020
income security to participate, you have to have access to a computer, programs, instruction,

00:12:03.020 --> 00:12:09.500
connections, the right jobs, it's a lot. So how do we take these barriers down one by one?

00:12:10.059 --> 00:12:14.539
So first you have to know about data science. And so the way that we've addressed that problem

00:12:14.539 --> 00:12:18.700
with our program is we actually go out into the community and we partner with community-based

00:12:18.700 --> 00:12:23.739
education associations like Historic East Baltimore Community Action Coalition and Heart

00:12:23.739 --> 00:12:29.580
Smiles, who train young people to get their high school diplomas, who train them to get

00:12:29.580 --> 00:12:35.099
technical training, and we teach them about the opportunities that are there in data science.

00:12:35.099 --> 00:12:40.940
We partner with them to recruit students for our program. Then how do we address the computer?

00:12:41.659 --> 00:12:46.619
So this is the thing that maybe kicked off all of this for me. I love Chromebooks, and you can get

00:12:46.619 --> 00:12:50.859
a Chromebook for $450. We've seen the power of this with education over the last couple of years

00:12:50.859 --> 00:12:56.619
with the pandemic. And it turns out that you can be a data scientist on a Chromebook. And this is

00:12:56.619 --> 00:13:01.979
where, again, RStudio and Posit have been a major player in what we've been able to do by creating

00:13:01.979 --> 00:13:07.020
RStudio Cloud. We were one of the first programs to jump onto that platform so that you can do all

00:13:07.020 --> 00:13:11.500
of your data science work directly on the cloud. It's such an incredible tool, and I'm so grateful

00:13:11.500 --> 00:13:16.380
that we've been able to use that to help train people. And so you can be a data scientist on

00:13:16.380 --> 00:13:21.419
a Chromebook. You can use Google Slides and Google Sheets, and you can use RStudio, and you can

00:13:21.419 --> 00:13:24.940
teach people how to do it. And they don't need a MacBook Pro to be a data scientist.

00:13:26.700 --> 00:13:31.900
There's also barriers to entry. You know, if you need to buy a MacBook Pro, it costs you $3,000.

00:13:31.900 --> 00:13:36.460
If your family only made $18,000 last year, you can't participate in a program like this.

00:13:37.260 --> 00:13:42.219
So with funding from Johns Hopkins originally, later from the Abel Foundation, we actually pay

00:13:42.219 --> 00:13:46.380
the students to complete the courses. So as they finish our massive online open courses, they

00:13:46.380 --> 00:13:49.659
earn money so that they can participate in it like a part-time job.

00:13:51.500 --> 00:13:53.900
Thank you, yeah. Thanks to Abel. Thanks to Johns Hopkins.

00:13:57.659 --> 00:14:01.340
They also need access to the right kind of instruction and the appropriate programs.

00:14:02.059 --> 00:14:07.659
So here's where R really shines. Why would we use R? I get asked this question all the time.

00:14:07.659 --> 00:14:12.140
We built our entire training program around R. I know that there's also Python people here in

00:14:12.140 --> 00:14:16.299
we love Python too, but we built our whole program around R, and I get asked a lot why we did that.

00:14:17.020 --> 00:14:20.219
And the reason why is we wanted to minimize the time to magic.

00:14:21.020 --> 00:14:25.340
So with just a few lines of code, R Markdown with just a few lines of code can put a website

00:14:25.340 --> 00:14:29.419
up on the web that's interactive that you can show off to your friends and to your family.

00:14:30.940 --> 00:14:36.859
With things like the big R query package and dbplyr, you can connect to massive databases

00:14:36.859 --> 00:14:40.140
and analyze huge collections of data with just a few lines of code.

00:14:40.700 --> 00:14:46.219
And with things like Shiny, Flex Dashboard, Shiny Dashboards, those, you can also write just a few

00:14:46.219 --> 00:14:50.700
lines of code here. It's like 34 lines of code that creates an interactive NHANES website.

00:14:51.820 --> 00:14:56.859
So with minimizing time to magic, we can train people very quickly to do incredible things.

00:14:58.140 --> 00:15:02.059
And then we can build a program around it. We can build a community around it that helps support

00:15:02.059 --> 00:15:06.940
people as they go through and they learn how to do data science. We do this on Basecamp.

00:15:07.820 --> 00:15:11.099
You can also do it on Slack or any other community building platform.

00:15:11.099 --> 00:15:14.460
But there has to be both an online and an in-person component.

00:15:16.219 --> 00:15:20.539
So then the last part is you have to think about, okay, say we have a training program.

00:15:20.539 --> 00:15:22.859
So we've trained them to do it. We've built it in R.

00:15:22.859 --> 00:15:26.619
Then they need access to connections. They need to be able to actually get a job.

00:15:27.820 --> 00:15:32.700
And so here we can, again, leverage the R community, the people here in the audience today,

00:15:32.700 --> 00:15:35.820
to help make connections between the young people that we're training

00:15:35.820 --> 00:15:38.299
and the broader community and opportunities that are out there.

00:15:39.500 --> 00:15:43.500
And this ecosystem really works. We've had 80% success rate in our Johns

00:15:43.500 --> 00:15:46.780
Hopkins pilot that I'm going to tell you a little bit about and completing the training.

00:15:46.780 --> 00:15:50.140
Just to give you some idea, massive online open courses in general,

00:15:50.140 --> 00:15:53.020
the completion rate hovers somewhere between 2% and 5%.

00:15:53.820 --> 00:15:59.820
So 80% completion rate for this massive online open sequence is an incredible testament to the

00:15:59.820 --> 00:16:02.619
will and intelligence of the people that we're training in the community.

00:16:06.380 --> 00:16:14.299
So after they finish the training program, though, we want to put them into opportunities

00:16:14.299 --> 00:16:18.780
that can help change their lives. And so the reality is there are significant

00:16:18.780 --> 00:16:25.500
barriers to entry to these jobs, but we've partnered with programs that support internships

00:16:25.500 --> 00:16:30.299
that represent a soft landing place. We teach people data science in 16 weeks.

00:16:30.299 --> 00:16:34.460
That is not a lot of time to learn data science and learn how to be a data scientist.

00:16:34.539 --> 00:16:38.059
So we partner with programs like Urban Alliance, and we have a couple of people here,

00:16:38.619 --> 00:16:40.940
Chaz and LaShonda from Urban Alliance. I don't know where they're sitting,

00:16:40.940 --> 00:16:43.500
but they're also in the audience here today, over there.

00:16:44.140 --> 00:16:48.780
And they're helping us build internship programs that support the long component of training

00:16:48.780 --> 00:16:53.739
that's developing the soft skills, developing the approach to work that will let them be

00:16:53.739 --> 00:16:57.260
in these careers long term. So I'm going to tell you a little bit now

00:16:57.260 --> 00:17:02.619
about our pilot that we ran in Baltimore. This is what the whole pilot has felt like.

00:17:03.340 --> 00:17:08.219
We started this off with just an idea and absolutely no program.

00:17:08.219 --> 00:17:13.979
And so at every turn, it's felt like we're barely getting the train tracks together in time

00:17:13.979 --> 00:17:18.859
to be able to continue to run the program. So this is how it started.

00:17:18.859 --> 00:17:23.900
In February 2018, we started developing content for our data science training program.

00:17:24.459 --> 00:17:29.260
We met with HBCAC, Historic East Baltimore Community Action Coalition, in April of 2018,

00:17:29.260 --> 00:17:32.699
and we told them we were developing a program and we were excited about working with them.

00:17:33.339 --> 00:17:36.060
They got very excited and they said, can we start tomorrow?

00:17:36.060 --> 00:17:38.780
Remember, we had started developing our program in February.

00:17:38.780 --> 00:17:41.900
It was April. And so they said, okay,

00:17:41.900 --> 00:17:43.979
we'll give you a little time. We'll start in May.

00:17:46.060 --> 00:17:50.140
We had to develop this much content between February and May.

00:17:50.140 --> 00:17:55.339
So we're talking 12 courses that cover everything from how to use computers,

00:17:55.339 --> 00:18:00.219
to how do you organize projects, to the tidyverse, to written and oral communication,

00:18:00.219 --> 00:18:04.699
to how to get a job. 12 courses in five months.

00:18:05.500 --> 00:18:08.140
So this was me. I was a little stressed.

00:18:08.140 --> 00:18:09.900
I was worried that we wouldn't be able to do it.

00:18:10.699 --> 00:18:13.819
But fortunately, we had some really incredible help.

00:18:13.819 --> 00:18:16.380
So at the time, there are two people I particularly want to call out,

00:18:16.380 --> 00:18:19.979
Shannon Ellis and Abuzar Hadivand, who are postdocs at my group.

00:18:19.979 --> 00:18:25.020
One was an economist working on studying how the outcomes of these massive online open courses.

00:18:25.020 --> 00:18:26.219
And one was a geneticist.

00:18:26.859 --> 00:18:30.780
But they pitched in and they said, we can build this whole program in that much time.

00:18:31.500 --> 00:18:33.339
So they assembled this collaborative team.

00:18:33.339 --> 00:18:37.819
And on GitHub, using R Markdown, we built this entire program in that much time.

00:18:38.780 --> 00:18:41.020
We did have some challenges along the way, though.

00:18:41.020 --> 00:18:45.500
As we were building the program, the courses, like getting and cleaning data,

00:18:45.500 --> 00:18:48.859
were being updated because new packages would come out.

00:18:49.739 --> 00:18:52.459
So this is a plot on the x-axis is time.

00:18:53.099 --> 00:18:55.660
Thousands of R scripts after the start of a program.

00:18:55.660 --> 00:18:59.099
And on the y-axis is the usage of different packages.

00:18:59.099 --> 00:19:01.020
There's one that kind of stands out.

00:19:01.020 --> 00:19:03.500
And that's because right in the middle of when we're developing these courses,

00:19:03.500 --> 00:19:07.579
dplyr comes out, rendering half of our program totally valueless.

00:19:07.579 --> 00:19:08.859
And we have to start from scratch.

00:19:09.500 --> 00:19:10.140
Thanks, Hadley.

00:19:12.859 --> 00:19:16.300
So what we had to do is regenerate all of our materials.

00:19:16.300 --> 00:19:21.579
And we now pay very careful attention to what the RStudio and Posit folks are doing

00:19:21.660 --> 00:19:23.739
on their GitHub repos as we're developing courses.

00:19:24.859 --> 00:19:25.819
We built this program.

00:19:25.819 --> 00:19:27.660
And so now we were ready to start training people.

00:19:28.219 --> 00:19:30.140
So we thought, well, let's start May 1st.

00:19:30.140 --> 00:19:31.500
How long does the program last?

00:19:32.380 --> 00:19:33.339
They asked me.

00:19:33.339 --> 00:19:34.380
We'd never run it before.

00:19:34.380 --> 00:19:35.979
In fact, we had just built the program.

00:19:36.619 --> 00:19:38.459
I don't know how long the program lasts.

00:19:38.459 --> 00:19:39.660
Let's call it 12 weeks.

00:19:40.380 --> 00:19:42.459
So I told them we were going to do it in 12 weeks.

00:19:42.459 --> 00:19:46.060
Shannon, Abuzar, and I said, OK, we're going to finish it by August 31st.

00:19:46.939 --> 00:19:50.140
Despite us still having to fix up courses, all the bugs,

00:19:50.140 --> 00:19:53.420
our two pilot candidates finished in about 14 weeks.

00:19:53.420 --> 00:19:54.300
16 weeks, sorry.

00:19:55.260 --> 00:19:56.459
So that was pretty incredible.

00:19:56.459 --> 00:19:58.699
We took two young people from HBCAC.

00:19:58.699 --> 00:20:00.619
They'd never heard of data science before.

00:20:00.619 --> 00:20:03.339
We got them through an entire 12-course MOOC sequence.

00:20:03.339 --> 00:20:04.699
They both finished.

00:20:04.699 --> 00:20:05.420
It was awesome.

00:20:06.699 --> 00:20:09.180
Now they'd finished the data science training program.

00:20:09.180 --> 00:20:11.339
And we realized we got to get them a job.

00:20:12.459 --> 00:20:16.219
And so there's a bit of a challenge that we ran into that you may have run into sometimes

00:20:16.219 --> 00:20:17.420
in your search for jobs.

00:20:18.300 --> 00:20:21.500
This is the roles and responsibilities you may experience that you need to do

00:20:21.500 --> 00:20:22.619
once you get on the job.

00:20:23.260 --> 00:20:25.739
And this might be the job experience they're asking for.

00:20:27.339 --> 00:20:28.459
We saw that a lot.

00:20:28.459 --> 00:20:32.459
We saw that there were jobs that we knew that our graduates could perform

00:20:32.459 --> 00:20:34.859
but were not necessarily advertised in the right way.

00:20:35.819 --> 00:20:38.380
Moreover, we ran into the Fair Labor and Standards Act.

00:20:38.380 --> 00:20:41.260
And I learned more about the legal requirements around employment

00:20:41.260 --> 00:20:43.260
than I would care to repeat.

00:20:43.260 --> 00:20:47.099
But the basic idea is that because they're not computer scientists,

00:20:47.180 --> 00:20:50.300
they actually write text and they write prose and things like that,

00:20:50.300 --> 00:20:54.219
they don't qualify to be exempt employees unless they have a bachelor's degree.

00:20:54.219 --> 00:20:56.619
So we need them to be hourly data scientist jobs,

00:20:57.260 --> 00:20:59.900
which it turns out a few companies have, but many don't.

00:21:01.500 --> 00:21:02.459
So we're this close.

00:21:03.099 --> 00:21:04.459
We train these young people.

00:21:04.459 --> 00:21:05.260
They're brilliant.

00:21:05.260 --> 00:21:06.540
They finish the program.

00:21:06.540 --> 00:21:09.180
But we can't quite get them into the finish line.

00:21:09.739 --> 00:21:10.939
So what are we going to do about this?

00:21:10.939 --> 00:21:14.540
How are we going to actually get them to the point where they can be employed

00:21:14.540 --> 00:21:16.939
and they can move to a different place in their life?

00:21:17.979 --> 00:21:19.420
So I did what anyone would do.

00:21:19.420 --> 00:21:23.180
I called a friend of mine, an old family friend who was a consultant for IBM.

00:21:23.180 --> 00:21:25.020
And I said, let's start a consulting company.

00:21:25.660 --> 00:21:28.540
And so he and I started a consulting company.

00:21:28.540 --> 00:21:32.140
And we would do data science consulting work for companies all around the country.

00:21:32.699 --> 00:21:34.859
We would do them for Fortune 500 companies,

00:21:34.859 --> 00:21:37.420
for small companies, small mom and pop shops.

00:21:37.420 --> 00:21:39.739
And all of the data science work that was being done

00:21:39.739 --> 00:21:41.660
was being done by graduates of our program

00:21:41.660 --> 00:21:44.300
that we were hiring from the training program.

00:21:44.939 --> 00:21:45.739
This worked great.

00:21:46.699 --> 00:21:48.459
Graduates did an amazing job.

00:21:48.459 --> 00:21:49.260
We were able to do it.

00:21:49.260 --> 00:21:53.420
But we were a bootstrapped, bespoke data science consulting company.

00:21:53.420 --> 00:21:56.780
And ultimately, that's not the way that this is going to work going forward.

00:21:58.939 --> 00:22:02.300
So the next part of our story is we brought on Ashley Johnson,

00:22:02.300 --> 00:22:04.060
who's here today as a core member of our team

00:22:04.060 --> 00:22:06.619
and is the program manager for Datatrail.

00:22:06.619 --> 00:22:11.420
And she managed, through a lot of hard work, blood, sweat, and tears,

00:22:12.060 --> 00:22:14.380
to get our HR systems at Johns Hopkins,

00:22:14.380 --> 00:22:18.219
which is a massive organization where HR does not move quickly,

00:22:18.219 --> 00:22:22.060
to create a new job code so that we could hire people at Johns Hopkins

00:22:22.060 --> 00:22:24.699
specifically with the credentials from our program.

00:22:24.699 --> 00:22:27.260
This is an incredible testament to Ashley's patience

00:22:27.260 --> 00:22:29.180
and brilliance getting this through the system.

00:22:29.180 --> 00:22:31.260
And it allowed us to hire Davon Person,

00:22:31.260 --> 00:22:32.619
who's a graduate of our program,

00:22:32.619 --> 00:22:35.900
to be the main TA for all of our future training cohorts.

00:22:37.020 --> 00:22:40.699
This kind of work has to be done by advocates within an organization.

00:22:40.699 --> 00:22:42.459
This isn't data science work.

00:22:42.459 --> 00:22:46.459
This is the hard blocking and tackling that needs to be done

00:22:46.459 --> 00:22:49.500
by each and every one of us if we want to build new opportunities

00:22:49.500 --> 00:22:51.180
where there weren't opportunities before.

00:22:51.180 --> 00:22:52.060
Build new bridges.

00:22:53.099 --> 00:22:55.900
We have this phrase that we always say when we're building this program.

00:22:55.900 --> 00:22:57.579
Hard things are hard to do.

00:22:57.579 --> 00:23:00.300
When you want to make a big change in the way the world works,

00:23:00.300 --> 00:23:01.500
it's not going to be easy.

00:23:01.500 --> 00:23:02.619
It's going to be hard.

00:23:02.619 --> 00:23:04.300
And that means it's going to be hard to do,

00:23:04.300 --> 00:23:06.380
but it's worth doing even though it is hard.

00:23:07.819 --> 00:23:09.739
So I think I'm going to take another brief pause,

00:23:10.459 --> 00:23:14.219
and I'm going to have all of you think about some time you accomplished something.

00:23:14.219 --> 00:23:15.819
Something that was really hard,

00:23:15.819 --> 00:23:17.660
that you're really proud that you did,

00:23:17.660 --> 00:23:20.140
even though it took a lot of work and it was kind of painful.

00:23:20.140 --> 00:23:21.099
Tell your neighbor about it.

00:23:21.099 --> 00:23:23.579
We'll give you another couple of minutes, and then we'll come back.

00:25:39.739 --> 00:25:45.900
All right.

00:25:52.380 --> 00:25:53.579
We'll jump back into it.

00:26:03.979 --> 00:26:04.300
All right.

00:26:04.300 --> 00:26:05.420
I'm stoked about this.

00:26:05.420 --> 00:26:08.540
Everybody was very excited to tell each other about their accomplishments.

00:26:08.540 --> 00:26:09.099
That's great.

00:26:09.099 --> 00:26:10.060
I'm excited about it.

00:26:10.699 --> 00:26:13.020
Hopefully, I'll get to hear some of them later from some of you.

00:26:14.619 --> 00:26:17.260
So again, hard things are hard, but they're worth doing,

00:26:17.260 --> 00:26:18.939
as you all just were telling each other

00:26:18.939 --> 00:26:20.859
about something that you were really proud of,

00:26:20.859 --> 00:26:22.300
but it took a lot of work to do.

00:26:22.939 --> 00:26:25.180
So it's exciting to be a part of those things.

00:26:25.180 --> 00:26:27.339
It's exciting and compelling to be part of something

00:26:27.339 --> 00:26:29.579
that feels like it's really important,

00:26:29.579 --> 00:26:30.859
even if it takes a lot of work.

00:26:32.300 --> 00:26:34.859
I'm going to tell you a little bit about the impact of this program

00:26:34.859 --> 00:26:37.900
and what it's meant to the people in the community and to us.

00:26:38.859 --> 00:26:40.939
So first, I wanted to mention Devon, who's here today.

00:26:40.939 --> 00:26:45.020
Again, I can't remember where he is, but Devon is our lead.

00:26:45.020 --> 00:26:45.900
There he is.

00:26:45.900 --> 00:26:46.380
All right.

00:26:49.660 --> 00:26:52.380
Devon is our curriculum lead for Datatrail.

00:26:52.380 --> 00:26:55.260
He's a graduate of the program, an incredible guy.

00:26:55.260 --> 00:26:57.420
I knew Devon was going to be the right guy for our program

00:26:57.420 --> 00:27:00.939
when we had a dinner at our house for all the Datatrail trainees.

00:27:00.939 --> 00:27:03.420
He came to my house, and he spent the whole dinner

00:27:03.420 --> 00:27:06.619
teaching my, at the time, eight-year-old son how to play chess.

00:27:07.579 --> 00:27:10.859
Unfortunately, that's bad for me, because now I get beat all the time at chess.

00:27:11.660 --> 00:27:15.420
But it was a great testament to the incredible talent that he has

00:27:15.420 --> 00:27:17.339
for helping people learn how to do things.

00:27:17.339 --> 00:27:19.420
So it's so great to have him as part of the program.

00:27:20.380 --> 00:27:24.939
Another incredible part of this program is that one of our graduates,

00:27:25.660 --> 00:27:29.020
while working at Problem Forward, worked on an HBO documentary

00:27:29.020 --> 00:27:31.339
called The Slow Hustle, if any of you have seen it.

00:27:31.339 --> 00:27:33.339
If not, you should definitely go out and see it.

00:27:33.339 --> 00:27:36.859
They did a bunch of analysis of the historic redlining

00:27:36.859 --> 00:27:38.699
in Baltimore's community that prevented people

00:27:38.699 --> 00:27:41.260
from buying houses in different communities within Baltimore.

00:27:41.819 --> 00:27:43.660
It's quite a famous problem around the world,

00:27:43.660 --> 00:27:48.459
but in Baltimore, it's particularly transparent how big a problem it was.

00:27:48.459 --> 00:27:51.180
And so it was credited, actually, in the movie credits

00:27:51.180 --> 00:27:55.900
for their analysis of the data that showed this redlining.

00:27:55.900 --> 00:27:59.579
It was really an unbelievable effort that was made by a Datatrail graduate.

00:28:01.260 --> 00:28:01.660
Thank you.

00:28:01.660 --> 00:28:01.900
Yeah.

00:28:01.900 --> 00:28:08.300
And so this is an example of a quote.

00:28:08.300 --> 00:28:11.420
We collect quotes from all the people that come from the program.

00:28:11.420 --> 00:28:14.140
And so it says, it gave me a new direction and taught me

00:28:14.140 --> 00:28:16.780
you can be different, go a different route than your parents,

00:28:16.780 --> 00:28:18.780
not always hanging on to what society tells you.

00:28:18.780 --> 00:28:20.300
You can follow your own protocol.

00:28:20.859 --> 00:28:23.660
So it just gave me a sense like a new world or a new field

00:28:23.660 --> 00:28:25.180
and a new life that I got to see.

00:28:26.140 --> 00:28:28.140
It's such an incredible thing to be a mentor.

00:28:28.140 --> 00:28:31.099
It's such an incredible thing to be a person that makes a connection

00:28:31.099 --> 00:28:33.900
to a new field, to a new opportunity.

00:28:33.900 --> 00:28:36.780
And it's been incredibly rewarding to see that happen,

00:28:36.780 --> 00:28:40.619
not just for us, but watch it scale as Davon makes connections for people,

00:28:40.619 --> 00:28:42.380
as Candace makes connections for people,

00:28:42.380 --> 00:28:44.219
as Ashley makes connections for people.

00:28:45.979 --> 00:28:47.739
But we did learn some lessons along the way.

00:28:48.459 --> 00:28:50.619
I mentioned that we were a train that was constantly

00:28:50.619 --> 00:28:52.459
trying to take things off the track.

00:28:52.459 --> 00:28:56.540
This was almost all due to the fact that I'm a biostatistician by training.

00:28:56.540 --> 00:28:59.260
I don't know the first thing about building a community organization

00:28:59.260 --> 00:29:02.380
and had to learn over and over and over again

00:29:02.380 --> 00:29:05.900
things that people who work in the field have known for a long time.

00:29:05.900 --> 00:29:08.380
We learn those by listening, by paying attention,

00:29:08.380 --> 00:29:10.140
by spending time in those communities,

00:29:10.140 --> 00:29:11.739
but they're important and hard lessons.

00:29:12.939 --> 00:29:15.020
One of the most important things we learned

00:29:15.020 --> 00:29:17.180
is that I'm here at a data science conference,

00:29:17.180 --> 00:29:21.979
at our conference, but data science is actually the easy part of all of this.

00:29:21.979 --> 00:29:24.859
The young people that go through our program are bright.

00:29:24.859 --> 00:29:26.459
They're good at computers.

00:29:26.459 --> 00:29:28.699
Pretty soon they're teaching us about data science.

00:29:28.780 --> 00:29:30.219
That's not the hard part.

00:29:30.219 --> 00:29:32.060
The hard part is everything around it.

00:29:32.060 --> 00:29:33.819
All the stuff that comes up in somebody's life,

00:29:34.380 --> 00:29:35.819
you know, housing falling through,

00:29:35.819 --> 00:29:37.579
not being able to get transportation,

00:29:37.579 --> 00:29:39.339
not having the access to the resources,

00:29:39.339 --> 00:29:41.099
not having access to the connections of people

00:29:41.099 --> 00:29:44.060
that can hook you up with a job or an opportunity.

00:29:44.060 --> 00:29:46.459
Those are the things that really take work

00:29:46.459 --> 00:29:47.819
to make something like this happen.

00:29:49.420 --> 00:29:52.459
The other thing that we learned is that building trust takes time.

00:29:52.939 --> 00:29:54.939
You know, we're working in a community,

00:29:54.939 --> 00:29:57.579
we're working, you know, we come from Johns Hopkins at the time,

00:29:57.579 --> 00:29:59.260
now from the Hutch, you know,

00:29:59.260 --> 00:30:01.739
and we're making these connections to community-based organizations

00:30:01.739 --> 00:30:04.060
who've been working in those communities for a long time.

00:30:04.060 --> 00:30:07.660
But we're new, you know, we're not part of that community yet.

00:30:07.660 --> 00:30:10.060
And it takes time and it takes effort

00:30:10.060 --> 00:30:13.099
and it takes being there all the time consistently

00:30:13.099 --> 00:30:14.699
to be able to build that trust

00:30:14.699 --> 00:30:17.900
so that you can actually build a relationship that will last

00:30:17.900 --> 00:30:20.140
and will create people that move on to the next step.

00:30:20.939 --> 00:30:23.819
You know, it's hard to tell somebody you just met what's really going on.

00:30:24.540 --> 00:30:27.180
One of the things that's always the biggest challenge in our program

00:30:27.739 --> 00:30:29.339
is getting people to ask questions.

00:30:29.979 --> 00:30:34.060
It's intimidating to ask questions when you're starting something new.

00:30:34.060 --> 00:30:37.339
It's a scary thing to admit you don't know something.

00:30:37.339 --> 00:30:39.819
And so it's an important part of the program to build trust,

00:30:39.819 --> 00:30:41.180
to build those connections

00:30:41.180 --> 00:30:43.579
so that people can comfortably ask you what's wrong,

00:30:44.140 --> 00:30:46.380
tell you what's wrong, ask you for help.

00:30:46.380 --> 00:30:49.500
It's one of the things I appreciate to an incredible degree

00:30:49.500 --> 00:30:53.339
about the community here is that we're open to questions,

00:30:53.339 --> 00:30:55.500
that when people email you or tweet at you

00:30:55.500 --> 00:30:57.260
or send you a GitHub request,

00:30:57.500 --> 00:31:00.939
you answer those questions politely and kindly and with compassion.

00:31:00.939 --> 00:31:03.420
It means the world to people who are just starting out.

00:31:05.260 --> 00:31:07.979
And we also need to be able to scale employment and internships.

00:31:08.619 --> 00:31:11.579
Our original idea was basically born out of panic.

00:31:11.579 --> 00:31:13.900
I hadn't really thought through how we're going to get people jobs

00:31:13.900 --> 00:31:15.819
at the end of this training program we started.

00:31:15.819 --> 00:31:16.619
That's my fault.

00:31:17.660 --> 00:31:18.780
We needed something a little better

00:31:18.780 --> 00:31:20.619
than just starting a random consulting company.

00:31:21.420 --> 00:31:25.020
And so we need to be able to scale those employment opportunities

00:31:25.020 --> 00:31:27.020
and those internship opportunities.

00:31:27.020 --> 00:31:29.020
And this is where partnerships with organizations

00:31:29.020 --> 00:31:30.699
that know what they're doing is critical.

00:31:31.260 --> 00:31:32.939
So we've been working with the Urban Alliance

00:31:33.500 --> 00:31:36.859
who has a whole program and a whole system

00:31:36.859 --> 00:31:39.260
for managing internships for young people

00:31:39.260 --> 00:31:41.819
who come from communities like the one we're trying to serve.

00:31:42.939 --> 00:31:45.900
And so we're partnering with them to be able to run these internships

00:31:45.900 --> 00:31:47.900
in a long-term and sustainable way.

00:31:49.739 --> 00:31:50.939
We also need advocates.

00:31:51.579 --> 00:31:53.260
So one of the things that we've realized

00:31:53.260 --> 00:31:54.459
as we're going through this program

00:31:54.459 --> 00:31:56.219
is the thing that Problem Forward did,

00:31:56.219 --> 00:31:58.619
it wasn't that it was a data science consulting company.

00:31:58.619 --> 00:32:01.099
It wasn't that it was related to the training program.

00:32:01.099 --> 00:32:03.819
It was that we could advocate on behalf of young people

00:32:03.819 --> 00:32:04.859
who come out of these communities,

00:32:04.859 --> 00:32:06.540
who are talented individuals,

00:32:06.540 --> 00:32:09.020
who have credentials that maybe look a little different,

00:32:09.020 --> 00:32:11.420
who maybe don't have all of the background

00:32:11.420 --> 00:32:14.459
that other people might have when they're first starting out,

00:32:14.459 --> 00:32:17.180
but that are really talented and could be spectacular

00:32:17.180 --> 00:32:18.619
if just given a chance.

00:32:18.619 --> 00:32:21.180
And so within all organizations, we need those advocates.

00:32:21.180 --> 00:32:22.780
And those advocates have to be people like you,

00:32:23.339 --> 00:32:24.380
people like me,

00:32:24.380 --> 00:32:26.300
people who have opportunity already

00:32:26.300 --> 00:32:28.300
and can reach out and try to support somebody else

00:32:28.300 --> 00:32:30.699
as they go through that same journey that we all went through,

00:32:30.699 --> 00:32:33.180
that I had to go through when I came from Idaho to get to here.

00:32:35.180 --> 00:32:37.819
And the other thing we need is mutually intensive learning.

00:32:37.819 --> 00:32:41.099
It's been an incredible experience, I think, for both sides,

00:32:41.099 --> 00:32:43.180
both people that are coming out of the training program

00:32:43.180 --> 00:32:45.579
and the mentors and teachers and hiring partners

00:32:46.140 --> 00:32:47.579
to learn about each other,

00:32:47.579 --> 00:32:48.939
to learn about the things we do well.

00:32:49.500 --> 00:32:52.619
You know, I don't know the first thing about Instagram and TikTok

00:32:52.619 --> 00:32:53.339
and all that kind of stuff,

00:32:53.339 --> 00:32:54.140
but I'm learning.

00:32:54.140 --> 00:32:55.099
I'm learning.

00:32:55.099 --> 00:32:57.099
That's how we're getting into new communities.

00:32:57.099 --> 00:32:58.619
And I'm learning that from the people

00:32:58.619 --> 00:33:00.219
that are in the training program.

00:33:00.219 --> 00:33:02.540
So I think that there's a way

00:33:02.540 --> 00:33:04.459
that we can learn from each other.

00:33:04.459 --> 00:33:06.699
It's not just teaching data science in one direction.

00:33:06.699 --> 00:33:08.939
It's also learning in the other direction as well.

00:33:08.939 --> 00:33:10.939
And that mutually intensive learning

00:33:10.939 --> 00:33:13.739
can really develop a relationship that lasts a long time.

00:33:16.060 --> 00:33:16.859
So what's the future?

00:33:16.859 --> 00:33:18.300
What's the future of Datatrail?

00:33:18.300 --> 00:33:19.420
I told you about the pilot.

00:33:19.420 --> 00:33:22.619
I told you about where we're in a great place with Datatrail now,

00:33:22.619 --> 00:33:24.300
and we're just starting to think about the future

00:33:24.300 --> 00:33:25.500
and how do we scale this up.

00:33:27.099 --> 00:33:30.060
So our Datatrail model has three big components now.

00:33:30.780 --> 00:33:33.420
There's colleges and universities

00:33:33.420 --> 00:33:35.579
or training partners in general.

00:33:35.579 --> 00:33:37.739
They provide tutors and educational support.

00:33:38.699 --> 00:33:40.939
Then there's hiring partners or mentors.

00:33:40.939 --> 00:33:43.180
They provide the mentors and opportunities for the people

00:33:43.180 --> 00:33:44.619
once they finish the training program.

00:33:45.500 --> 00:33:48.219
And then we have nonprofit and community-based partners

00:33:48.219 --> 00:33:51.420
who do the hard work of supporting the whole person.

00:33:51.500 --> 00:33:53.660
Because when you're doing a training program

00:33:53.660 --> 00:33:54.780
and you're coming from a community

00:33:54.780 --> 00:33:56.140
that doesn't have a lot of resources,

00:33:56.859 --> 00:33:58.939
small things can cause big problems

00:33:58.939 --> 00:34:00.780
if you don't have the support you need

00:34:00.780 --> 00:34:02.459
to get through the training program.

00:34:02.459 --> 00:34:04.859
And so the three groups working together

00:34:04.859 --> 00:34:06.540
can really provide that infrastructure,

00:34:06.540 --> 00:34:08.620
that underlying infrastructure

00:34:08.620 --> 00:34:10.219
that gives somebody the opportunity

00:34:10.219 --> 00:34:12.780
to come from a community without a lot of opportunity

00:34:12.780 --> 00:34:14.780
into a place where they can be a leader in the field.

00:34:16.379 --> 00:34:17.659
So in Baltimore, we do this

00:34:17.659 --> 00:34:20.060
with the Johns Hopkins Data Science Lab

00:34:20.060 --> 00:34:22.060
providing the tutoring and support.

00:34:22.060 --> 00:34:24.139
So we've got Candace Savanen here,

00:34:24.139 --> 00:34:26.860
who was at the Johns Hopkins Data Science Lab,

00:34:26.860 --> 00:34:28.300
is now at the Fred Hutch Data Science Lab.

00:34:28.300 --> 00:34:30.300
I don't know where she is, but she could stand up.

00:34:30.300 --> 00:34:31.820
But she's helping to provide the tutoring

00:34:31.820 --> 00:34:32.780
and support with Davon.

00:34:34.780 --> 00:34:36.699
We have mentors and opportunities

00:34:36.699 --> 00:34:38.300
that we're building out with Urban Alliance.

00:34:39.020 --> 00:34:41.500
And then we have incredible nonprofit

00:34:41.500 --> 00:34:44.300
and community-based partnerships built in Baltimore

00:34:44.300 --> 00:34:46.219
that provide social and life support

00:34:46.219 --> 00:34:48.540
to the young people who are going through our programs

00:34:48.620 --> 00:34:50.300
so that if something comes up,

00:34:50.300 --> 00:34:51.739
they can get that support they need

00:34:51.739 --> 00:34:53.820
to stay in the program, to stick with it,

00:34:53.820 --> 00:34:55.739
to get the opportunity that they're going after.

00:34:57.179 --> 00:34:58.780
So this is how our program works now.

00:34:59.739 --> 00:35:02.459
From January to June, we're recruiting young people.

00:35:02.459 --> 00:35:04.620
We're getting into schools.

00:35:04.620 --> 00:35:06.620
We're providing content online.

00:35:06.620 --> 00:35:09.100
We're trying to get people excited about data science.

00:35:10.060 --> 00:35:11.979
And then from June to September,

00:35:11.979 --> 00:35:13.580
we're doing our training program.

00:35:13.580 --> 00:35:15.580
We're actually running the data trail courses.

00:35:15.580 --> 00:35:17.020
They're going through, they're getting paid

00:35:17.020 --> 00:35:18.540
as they complete the courses,

00:35:18.540 --> 00:35:20.219
and they're finishing the program.

00:35:20.219 --> 00:35:22.060
And we're also recruiting mentors.

00:35:22.060 --> 00:35:23.580
We're recruiting the people that are ultimately

00:35:23.580 --> 00:35:26.219
going to hire and mentor and manage the young people

00:35:26.219 --> 00:35:27.419
in their first opportunity.

00:35:28.459 --> 00:35:31.899
Then from September to June, they do an internship.

00:35:31.899 --> 00:35:33.979
This is supported by Urban Alliance.

00:35:33.979 --> 00:35:36.060
And this is a 10-hour-a-week internship

00:35:36.060 --> 00:35:37.419
where they get paid.

00:35:37.419 --> 00:35:39.260
It's virtual, and they get mentorship

00:35:39.260 --> 00:35:41.340
a couple of hours a week from a mentor

00:35:41.340 --> 00:35:43.020
at a hiring company or a partner.

00:35:43.979 --> 00:35:45.500
This is how the program works now.

00:35:45.820 --> 00:35:47.820
And so there's an opportunity for you

00:35:47.820 --> 00:35:49.820
to get involved with us at DataTrail

00:35:49.820 --> 00:35:50.860
if you're interested.

00:35:51.659 --> 00:35:52.780
There's two different ways.

00:35:53.659 --> 00:35:57.100
One is the more heavy-duty way,

00:35:57.100 --> 00:35:58.699
which is start your own data trail

00:35:58.699 --> 00:35:59.820
in your own community.

00:36:00.459 --> 00:36:02.459
And the other way is to hire or mentor

00:36:02.459 --> 00:36:04.459
data trail graduates from our program.

00:36:05.419 --> 00:36:06.780
So I'm going to start with starting

00:36:06.780 --> 00:36:09.020
your own data trail program.

00:36:09.020 --> 00:36:11.419
We talked a little bit about doing hard things.

00:36:11.419 --> 00:36:13.979
And we did a hard thing to set this thing up,

00:36:14.780 --> 00:36:16.780
and we've paved a lot of the ground for you.

00:36:17.580 --> 00:36:18.860
So if you're interested in starting

00:36:18.860 --> 00:36:20.540
your own data trail community,

00:36:20.540 --> 00:36:22.540
you can reach out to Ashley Johnson,

00:36:22.540 --> 00:36:24.620
to myself, and we can provide you

00:36:24.620 --> 00:36:26.379
with a lot of the background and materials

00:36:26.379 --> 00:36:28.060
you need to build this program

00:36:28.060 --> 00:36:28.780
in your community.

00:36:29.340 --> 00:36:31.020
We can provide startup documents,

00:36:31.739 --> 00:36:33.340
relationship agreements.

00:36:33.340 --> 00:36:34.379
We can give you information

00:36:34.379 --> 00:36:35.659
on how to get funded.

00:36:35.659 --> 00:36:38.459
We provide free courses so you can access them

00:36:38.459 --> 00:36:40.379
and train people in data science.

00:36:40.379 --> 00:36:41.500
And then we provide access

00:36:41.500 --> 00:36:42.939
to the data trail community

00:36:42.939 --> 00:36:44.379
so you can talk to the people

00:36:44.379 --> 00:36:45.899
who are building it in Baltimore

00:36:45.899 --> 00:36:46.780
and around the country.

00:36:48.780 --> 00:36:52.300
I'm very excited because the first data trail franchise

00:36:52.300 --> 00:36:53.260
has started already.

00:36:54.060 --> 00:36:57.500
So Madhu and Melanie contacted us.

00:36:57.500 --> 00:36:59.020
They're at Mount Sinai Health System

00:36:59.020 --> 00:37:00.139
in New York City,

00:37:00.139 --> 00:37:02.459
and they were really excited about data trail.

00:37:03.260 --> 00:37:05.739
And the two of them set up a data trail franchise

00:37:05.739 --> 00:37:08.139
that's running completely independently in New York

00:37:08.139 --> 00:37:10.780
and is now on its second cohort of graduates,

00:37:10.780 --> 00:37:13.020
placing people in the medical health system,

00:37:13.020 --> 00:37:15.179
placing them at jobs around New York City.

00:37:15.179 --> 00:37:16.300
It's amazing to see

00:37:17.020 --> 00:37:19.419
how just a couple of committed people

00:37:19.419 --> 00:37:21.179
can have such an incredible impact

00:37:21.179 --> 00:37:23.179
on the lives of young people in their community,

00:37:23.179 --> 00:37:24.780
and I'm so impressed with the work

00:37:24.780 --> 00:37:26.139
that Madhu and Melanie are doing.

00:37:26.139 --> 00:37:30.620
Yeah, it's awesome.

00:37:34.219 --> 00:37:35.500
So the other way you can get involved

00:37:35.500 --> 00:37:37.179
is to hire a mentor.

00:37:37.179 --> 00:37:38.540
So we're working with Urban Alliance,

00:37:38.540 --> 00:37:39.100
as I mentioned,

00:37:39.100 --> 00:37:40.620
and there's two ways that you can do this.

00:37:41.500 --> 00:37:43.580
You could hire data trail graduates

00:37:44.939 --> 00:37:45.659
into your company

00:37:45.659 --> 00:37:48.139
if you have internships that you want to support.

00:37:48.139 --> 00:37:49.419
It's part-time internships.

00:37:49.419 --> 00:37:51.020
They're remote, paid internships,

00:37:51.580 --> 00:37:53.500
and they can be supported by Urban Alliance

00:37:53.500 --> 00:37:54.219
and data trail.

00:37:54.219 --> 00:37:56.939
In other words, we support them on the technical side,

00:37:56.939 --> 00:37:58.139
and Urban Alliance supports them

00:37:58.139 --> 00:37:59.179
on the soft skills side.

00:38:00.139 --> 00:38:01.979
I'm incredibly excited to announce

00:38:01.979 --> 00:38:04.860
that Posit has committed to host

00:38:04.860 --> 00:38:06.620
two of these interns this fall

00:38:06.620 --> 00:38:07.820
from our data trail cohort,

00:38:07.820 --> 00:38:09.580
which is an amazing opportunity,

00:38:09.580 --> 00:38:10.379
and thank you so much.

00:38:15.659 --> 00:38:16.860
The other cool opportunity,

00:38:16.860 --> 00:38:18.860
and this I'm also wildly excited about,

00:38:19.419 --> 00:38:21.500
is that you can mentor data trail graduates

00:38:21.500 --> 00:38:22.860
as an open source developer.

00:38:23.659 --> 00:38:25.820
So we could place people directly into companies,

00:38:25.820 --> 00:38:27.419
but there's also an incredible opportunity

00:38:27.419 --> 00:38:28.540
for our data trail grads

00:38:28.540 --> 00:38:30.060
to make an impact on the open source

00:38:30.060 --> 00:38:31.340
and open science community.

00:38:31.979 --> 00:38:33.739
And so the idea here is

00:38:33.739 --> 00:38:35.899
we get philanthropic and corporate funding

00:38:35.899 --> 00:38:37.100
to pay for the internship,

00:38:37.659 --> 00:38:39.659
and then we will recruit mentors

00:38:39.659 --> 00:38:41.100
from the open source community

00:38:41.739 --> 00:38:43.659
to work on their projects.

00:38:43.659 --> 00:38:46.620
And so Posit, again, has committed incredibly

00:38:46.620 --> 00:38:48.379
to fund one of these this fall.

00:38:48.379 --> 00:38:50.139
If you're an open source developer

00:38:50.139 --> 00:38:51.100
that's looking for somebody

00:38:51.100 --> 00:38:52.459
to work with you on your project

00:38:52.459 --> 00:38:54.620
and you're looking for a talented young person,

00:38:54.620 --> 00:38:56.540
you should come and talk to us after the event.

00:38:57.580 --> 00:38:59.580
And then the Abel Foundation has also agreed

00:38:59.580 --> 00:39:01.100
to fund one more this fall

00:39:01.100 --> 00:39:02.459
from our training program.

00:39:02.459 --> 00:39:04.459
And that represents our entire training cohort

00:39:04.459 --> 00:39:05.979
is going to get funded this year,

00:39:06.060 --> 00:39:08.459
and we're excited about building this over time.

00:39:09.179 --> 00:39:11.419
So if you have an idea about a program

00:39:11.419 --> 00:39:15.500
that if you want to either mentor a student this fall

00:39:16.060 --> 00:39:18.300
or you want to start thinking about next fall,

00:39:18.860 --> 00:39:19.580
get in touch.

00:39:19.580 --> 00:39:22.139
I've got the email addresses up here of Chaz Ackley,

00:39:22.139 --> 00:39:24.060
who's our Urban Alliance partner,

00:39:24.060 --> 00:39:25.979
the director of the Baltimore office,

00:39:25.979 --> 00:39:27.500
and Ashley Johnson,

00:39:27.500 --> 00:39:30.379
who's the director of the data trail program in Baltimore.

00:39:30.379 --> 00:39:32.620
And you can reach out to either of them or to me

00:39:32.620 --> 00:39:35.020
if you're excited about mentoring a data trail grad.

00:39:36.860 --> 00:39:39.020
I'd like to finish, though,

00:39:39.020 --> 00:39:40.699
talking about not just data trail,

00:39:40.699 --> 00:39:42.139
because this is a cool opportunity

00:39:42.139 --> 00:39:43.820
and we would love to work with all of you,

00:39:44.379 --> 00:39:45.340
but you can also do it

00:39:45.340 --> 00:39:46.780
in any other way that you feel like.

00:39:46.780 --> 00:39:47.979
I think just bringing it back

00:39:47.979 --> 00:39:49.580
to what I said at the beginning of the talk,

00:39:50.540 --> 00:39:52.540
this is an incredible opportunity to be together,

00:39:52.540 --> 00:39:54.139
to build community together,

00:39:54.139 --> 00:39:56.459
and I think that what Posit and our studio have done

00:39:56.459 --> 00:39:58.060
is just an amazing way

00:39:58.060 --> 00:40:00.379
to make us all feel part of the same community.

00:40:01.659 --> 00:40:03.899
One of the things that we should do

00:40:03.899 --> 00:40:05.020
is help each other,

00:40:05.100 --> 00:40:06.379
whether that's through data trail

00:40:06.379 --> 00:40:09.260
or through Openscapes or Our Ladies

00:40:09.260 --> 00:40:10.459
or Data Carpentry

00:40:10.459 --> 00:40:12.459
or any other program that you're excited about.

00:40:13.179 --> 00:40:14.860
And there's this quote that I love.

00:40:15.419 --> 00:40:17.500
I emailed my undergrad advisor

00:40:17.500 --> 00:40:19.500
when I first got my very first faculty job

00:40:19.500 --> 00:40:21.020
and I told him I was so excited about it.

00:40:21.020 --> 00:40:22.540
I got to live near my wife.

00:40:22.540 --> 00:40:23.899
I got to live in Baltimore.

00:40:23.899 --> 00:40:25.580
I got to do my dream job.

00:40:25.580 --> 00:40:26.860
And he wrote me back,

00:40:26.860 --> 00:40:29.100
but he was really glad to hear.

00:40:29.100 --> 00:40:32.939
And he said, mentorship is a debt you can't pay off.

00:40:32.939 --> 00:40:35.100
I had some mentors who helped me when I was young

00:40:35.100 --> 00:40:36.860
and I can never pay it off to them.

00:40:36.860 --> 00:40:39.179
I can only pay it forward to other people.

00:40:39.179 --> 00:40:41.899
And so he said, thank you for helping me pay off my debt.

00:40:42.620 --> 00:40:44.139
And I feel like we're all in this room

00:40:44.139 --> 00:40:45.899
owe a debt of gratitude to all of the people

00:40:45.899 --> 00:40:47.820
that have helped us be here today.

00:40:47.820 --> 00:40:50.219
And whichever way you choose to express that,

00:40:50.219 --> 00:40:51.419
I hope you'll think about ways

00:40:51.419 --> 00:40:54.219
that you can pay forward your debt.

00:40:55.899 --> 00:40:57.739
There's almost nothing more rewarding than this.

00:40:57.739 --> 00:40:59.260
It's been an incredible journey.

00:40:59.260 --> 00:41:01.179
And I think that the people here today,

00:41:01.179 --> 00:41:03.899
the Datatrail folks, the Urban Alliance folks,

00:41:03.899 --> 00:41:08.139
the HeartSmiles folks, the Hebcac folks,

00:41:08.139 --> 00:41:09.739
they're all here to say that this is one

00:41:09.739 --> 00:41:11.100
of the most rewarding things you can do

00:41:11.100 --> 00:41:12.939
is create opportunities for young people.

00:41:14.139 --> 00:41:15.419
With that, I'll thank you.

00:41:15.419 --> 00:41:17.020
And at the conclusion of the talk,

00:41:17.020 --> 00:41:18.300
after this is all over,

00:41:18.300 --> 00:41:20.300
I'm going to be hanging out up here in front

00:41:20.300 --> 00:41:23.260
with Ashley, with Chas, with Davon, with Candice.

00:41:23.260 --> 00:41:24.459
If you're excited about mentoring

00:41:24.459 --> 00:41:25.500
or talking about Datatrail,

00:41:25.500 --> 00:41:26.780
please come and hang out and talk

00:41:26.780 --> 00:41:28.780
and we'd love to get to talk to you.

00:41:28.780 --> 00:41:29.820
Thank you very much for your attention.

00:41:29.979 --> 00:41:44.300
Thanks, Jeff.

00:41:44.300 --> 00:41:49.899
Now we engage in light banter for one to two minutes

00:41:49.899 --> 00:41:51.820
until people ask questions

00:41:51.820 --> 00:41:54.139
and have a chance to upvote them.

00:41:55.100 --> 00:41:56.780
Light banter about ggplot2?

00:41:56.780 --> 00:41:57.340
Yeah, sure.

00:41:57.899 --> 00:42:01.100
I'm glad I got my digs in before the talk.

00:42:01.100 --> 00:42:03.340
Yeah, that was a good investment.

00:42:03.340 --> 00:42:04.620
I feel like that's the only reason

00:42:04.620 --> 00:42:06.699
I got the invitation was so Hadley got to say that.

00:42:08.379 --> 00:42:09.500
I was actually reading through,

00:42:09.500 --> 00:42:10.780
like, there's been a few.

00:42:10.780 --> 00:42:12.219
You also wrote one on tidy data

00:42:12.219 --> 00:42:14.139
that wasn't really, like, against tidy data.

00:42:14.139 --> 00:42:15.340
I was not against tidy data.

00:42:15.340 --> 00:42:16.860
No, that was, like, very much, like,

00:42:17.739 --> 00:42:19.500
these are some use cases where it's, like,

00:42:19.500 --> 00:42:22.459
not great for, and yeah, it was right.

00:42:22.459 --> 00:42:23.020
Oh, man.

00:42:23.020 --> 00:42:24.060
I'm getting all the grapes.

00:42:24.060 --> 00:42:25.899
Somebody save me with the question, please.

00:42:26.860 --> 00:42:27.260
Okay.

00:42:27.260 --> 00:42:28.620
We do have one question.

00:42:28.620 --> 00:42:29.179
One question.

00:42:29.179 --> 00:42:30.459
One to save you.

00:42:31.100 --> 00:42:34.300
Are the mentoring opportunities only available in Baltimore?

00:42:34.300 --> 00:42:37.100
No, these are remote online mentorship opportunities.

00:42:37.100 --> 00:42:39.500
So if you are an open source developer

00:42:39.500 --> 00:42:41.419
and are excited about mentoring a young person,

00:42:42.459 --> 00:42:44.219
it's going to get paid for by the Able Foundation.

00:42:44.219 --> 00:42:45.419
It's going to get paid for by Posit.

00:42:45.419 --> 00:42:48.060
So you just get an awesome mentee

00:42:48.060 --> 00:42:49.500
to work with you for a year.

00:42:49.500 --> 00:42:51.739
So if you're an open source developer anywhere,

00:42:51.739 --> 00:42:52.459
please reach out.

00:42:54.620 --> 00:42:55.120
Cool.

00:42:56.780 --> 00:42:58.939
And the next question,

00:42:58.939 --> 00:43:01.179
how have the program graduates been doing long-term?

00:43:02.540 --> 00:43:04.620
Yeah, they're all over the place.

00:43:04.620 --> 00:43:07.899
They're doing everything from data science jobs,

00:43:07.899 --> 00:43:09.500
but the kind of cool thing about it is,

00:43:09.500 --> 00:43:11.899
you know, people like Devon is working with us.

00:43:11.899 --> 00:43:12.780
We've got other young people

00:43:12.780 --> 00:43:14.219
that are working in data science jobs.

00:43:14.219 --> 00:43:16.780
One has converted to Python, which is great,

00:43:16.780 --> 00:43:20.139
but, you know, I won't say that too loudly.

00:43:20.780 --> 00:43:22.300
But then there's also some people

00:43:22.300 --> 00:43:23.500
that just took the training

00:43:23.500 --> 00:43:24.939
and then went in a different direction

00:43:24.939 --> 00:43:25.820
in what they cared about.

00:43:25.820 --> 00:43:27.580
I think one of the cool things about the program

00:43:27.580 --> 00:43:28.939
is we're catching young people

00:43:28.939 --> 00:43:30.620
at a really formative time of their life,

00:43:30.620 --> 00:43:33.179
so 17 to 23 or so.

00:43:33.179 --> 00:43:35.659
And I'm sure you all remember,

00:43:35.659 --> 00:43:37.659
you didn't exactly know what you wanted to do

00:43:37.659 --> 00:43:38.939
when you were 17.

00:43:38.939 --> 00:43:41.020
And so data science could be cool for a while

00:43:41.020 --> 00:43:42.060
and they learn some stuff from us

00:43:42.060 --> 00:43:43.580
and then they maybe go apply it,

00:43:43.580 --> 00:43:45.340
you know, the skills they learned somewhere else.

00:43:45.340 --> 00:43:46.620
And so we have some people

00:43:46.620 --> 00:43:47.979
that end up in data science careers,

00:43:47.979 --> 00:43:49.580
some people that go back to school,

00:43:49.580 --> 00:43:50.780
some people that end up, like,

00:43:50.780 --> 00:43:51.899
doing something totally different

00:43:51.899 --> 00:43:53.580
but kind of leveraging the training.

00:43:54.060 --> 00:43:56.060
But we keep in touch with all of them.

00:43:56.060 --> 00:43:57.820
And so, you know, I'm always texting

00:43:57.820 --> 00:44:00.379
with people that have graduated from the program

00:44:00.379 --> 00:44:03.500
and it's cool to see that community build over time.

00:44:03.500 --> 00:44:04.219
So, yeah.

00:44:04.219 --> 00:44:06.699
And what are some of the challenges you faced

00:44:06.699 --> 00:44:08.540
in terms of both kind of, like, buy-in

00:44:08.540 --> 00:44:10.540
and just, like, raising awareness of the program?

00:44:11.500 --> 00:44:11.979
Yeah.

00:44:11.979 --> 00:44:13.899
So I think that I tried to highlight

00:44:13.899 --> 00:44:15.260
a couple of the key issues,

00:44:15.260 --> 00:44:18.060
but, like, there's been a whole collection

00:44:18.060 --> 00:44:19.659
of issues in doing this.

00:44:19.659 --> 00:44:20.860
Everything from, you know,

00:44:20.860 --> 00:44:22.939
HR problems to legal problems

00:44:22.939 --> 00:44:24.219
to bureaucratic problems

00:44:24.219 --> 00:44:26.939
to, like, building data science program problems.

00:44:26.939 --> 00:44:29.179
And I think the core message, though,

00:44:29.179 --> 00:44:33.020
is that the thing that helps most

00:44:33.020 --> 00:44:35.419
is to think about the target at the end.

00:44:35.419 --> 00:44:38.540
So our goal is to help young people get opportunities.

00:44:38.540 --> 00:44:41.020
Sometimes that's by building a data science program,

00:44:41.020 --> 00:44:43.020
but sometimes it's by Ashley and I

00:44:43.020 --> 00:44:44.300
going to a million HR meetings

00:44:44.300 --> 00:44:46.219
to try to create a new job code.

00:44:46.219 --> 00:44:48.379
And so I think thinking about that target,

00:44:48.379 --> 00:44:49.979
like, what you're trying to create at the end

00:44:50.620 --> 00:44:51.820
gives you a lot of leeway

00:44:51.820 --> 00:44:53.899
to do all the things you need to do

00:44:53.899 --> 00:44:56.540
and then being flexible about learning new things.

00:44:56.540 --> 00:44:58.540
I think that's been the hard thing for me, definitely.

00:44:58.540 --> 00:45:00.060
I didn't know the first thing about,

00:45:00.060 --> 00:45:01.260
you know, I'm a biostatistician.

00:45:01.260 --> 00:45:02.300
What do I know about any of that?

00:45:02.300 --> 00:45:03.979
But I'm learning over time,

00:45:03.979 --> 00:45:06.540
and I feel like having smart people I work with helps.

00:45:07.580 --> 00:45:09.979
What about plans as you transition to the Hutch?

00:45:10.780 --> 00:45:11.899
Yeah, so we're getting ready

00:45:11.899 --> 00:45:13.659
to be able to run the program in Seattle,

00:45:13.659 --> 00:45:14.860
so I'm excited about that.

00:45:15.820 --> 00:45:17.500
And then it's running in New York.

00:45:17.500 --> 00:45:19.500
We have a couple of other ambitions

00:45:19.500 --> 00:45:21.179
about starting in a couple of other cities

00:45:21.179 --> 00:45:22.379
I can't announce quite yet,

00:45:22.379 --> 00:45:24.300
but that we're going to start soon.

00:45:24.300 --> 00:45:26.060
And so really now we're at the stage

00:45:26.060 --> 00:45:27.659
where we're excited about scaling it out.

00:45:27.659 --> 00:45:30.060
And so it's been running in Baltimore for a few years.

00:45:30.060 --> 00:45:31.340
It's successful in Baltimore,

00:45:31.340 --> 00:45:32.540
and I think it's the kind of program

00:45:32.540 --> 00:45:34.379
that can very easily run

00:45:34.379 --> 00:45:36.699
in a number of cities around the U.S. that I highlighted.

00:45:36.699 --> 00:45:38.699
And so we're really in this phase

00:45:38.699 --> 00:45:40.300
of trying to get connected to the right people

00:45:40.300 --> 00:45:42.219
who are excited about running those programs.

00:45:42.219 --> 00:45:42.620
So...

00:45:42.620 --> 00:45:43.899
Awesome. Thanks, Jeff.

00:45:43.899 --> 00:45:47.100
Really, that was, like, just amazing, uplifting keynote.

00:45:47.100 --> 00:45:48.300
So thank you so much.

00:45:48.300 --> 00:45:55.100
Appreciate it.

